The '''Ruvu weaver''' ('''''Ploceus holoxanthus''''') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Ploceidae]]. It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to eastern [[Tanzania]]. 

Initially described as a distinct species by [[Gustav Hartlaub]] in 1891, it was synonymized with the [[eastern golden weaver]] (''P. subaureus'') by the majority of later authorities. However, critical morphological analysis in 2021 confirmed it as being a distinct species. It can be generally distinguished from ''P. subaureus'' by the darker brown eye of the male and the lighter lower mandible of the female.<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal |last=Oschadleus |first=H. Dieter |last2=Andersson |first2=Staffan Andersson |last3=Baker |first3=Neil E. |date=2021-03-08 |title=History and biology of the reassigned Ruvu Weaver Ploceus holoxanthus |url=https://www.ajol.info/index.php/scopus/article/view/204524 |journal=Scopus: Journal of East African Ornithology |language=en |volume=41 |issue=1 |pages=1–12 |issn=2313-1799}}</ref> 

It has a very restricted distribution in Tanzania, being only found along the [[Ruvu River|Ruvu]], [[Wami River|Wami]], and [[Rufiji River|Rufiji]] [[Drainage basin|river basins]]. Several colonies are known from the vicinity of [[Morogoro]].<ref name=":0" /> 

